Teaching down on the side is way easier than a traditional forward down (you can also pair it with ‚Äúplay dead‚Äù or ‚Äúbang‚Äù if you like). Most cats when they‚Äôre switched on during training won‚Äôt want to lie forward - they might crouch, but you‚Äôre unlikely to get a proper lie down, so I prefer to teach this trick! It‚Äôs much less effort and more natural for your cat to learn.

We introduced Luna to her cousin Enzo recently. He is beautifully behaved and so is she, so it was pretty easy. Here‚Äôs how we did it:

1. Trading blankets months in advance
2. Luna explored his house whilst Enzo went for a walk 
3. Seeing each other through the window first 
4. Petting both in the same room 
5. Enzo in a calm down stay, Luna with the freedom to explore 
6. Luna in a stay, watching Enzo‚Äôs training
7. Rewards for both when not fixating
8. Allowing Luna to initiate contact
9. Calming sown & sleeping in the same room to finish! 

Remember, safety is always no. 1, stop if either the cat or dog are uncomfortable at any time and never push! End it on a good note and always respect boundaries.

1. Touch the your fingertip to your cat‚Äôs nose & click (it‚Äôs important that you click at the precise moment of the touch to build the correct association)
2. Once they understand the connection, wait for them to boop your finger and reward
3. Move your finger gradually further away
4. Build up to getting them to follow your finger around 
5. Add a verbal command

Accidents can happen to anyone! I‚Äôm a very experienced pet owner (20+ years of fostering, rescuing, handing-reared kittens, etc) and I have never gone through something like this before. This video is really personal but we wish we had been more prepared and hope our reflections help someone:

1. Know where your nearest vet & emergency hospital is (and their opening hours).
2. Save the vets‚Äô number in your phone & their location in maps/ Uber.
3. Research reasons why you might need to take your pet to the vet, how to move an injured animal, and how to do CPR.
4. Make sure you have lifetime insurance with at least ¬£3k cover, ideally more.

Minutes can matter. We are very lucky that Luna is okay as we had most of these ticked off. But we are even more ready now (although we hope it never happens again)!
